<section id="spending">
  <div class="inner">
    <div class="sec-num">Part Three</div>
    <h2>Has government spending really grown?</h2>
    <p class="lead">One argument in the property tax debate is that rising home values have produced surplus revenue and that spending has grown faster than the cost of services. Evaluating that claim requires adjusting the raw figures for two factors: inflation and population growth. This section presents both the unadjusted and adjusted numbers.</p>

    <h3 class="sp-h">Nominal and inflation-adjusted figures differ</h3>
    <p>From 2015 to 2024, total governmental-activities spending rose <b>87.5%</b> in raw (nominal) dollars. Over the same period the dollar lost value and Jacksonville added residents. Adjusting for inflation, real spending grew <b>42.2%</b>. Adjusting further for the <b>16.6%</b> population growth, real spending <b>per resident</b> grew about <b>22%</b> over nine years, or roughly <b>2.2% a year</b>.</p>

